        <p> Then we decided to use the &ldquo;hop-on hop-off downtown&rdquo; bus back to the Times Square and switch to the &ldquo;Uptown&rdquo; bus. Unfortunately we had to wait 30 minutes until a bus finally came. This was also so overcrowded that we quickly decided not to get in and prefer to go to an exhibition from National Geographic&rsquo;s. </p>
        <p> The whole thing is called Ocean Odyssey. This is a dive into the world's oceans, without getting wet or peeling out of the cozy clothes. This is a purely virtual tour, the only real water here, is a small fountain in the stairwell. There are also no real animals/corals here, but all the more monitors, projections and staff who explain everything to you. There are many small individual rooms in which something else always waits for you. The seals and the Kelbwald fell best. A place where you can learn a lot about our oceans and in casual you are also informed about environmental protection and without it being intrusive or with a raised index finger. </p>
        <p> After this exciting experience, Steffi finally wanted to eat a burger. She's been here for so long and we haven't had one yet. So we landed on the other side of the street in a small diner and ate delicious burgers. </p>

